                        <title>Letter from Charles N. Tenney to Adelaide E. Case</title>
                    </bibl>
                </head>

                <p> Charles Tenney writes Adelaide E. Case from Parkersburg, Va., describing his
                    arrival on the steamer Decatur and his imminent departure by railroad to
                    Grafton, Va. He suggests the happiness he derives from his correspondence with
                    Addie.</p>
            </div1>

        </front>


        <body id="d4">




            <div1 type="letter" n="1" id="d5">
                <head>Letter from Charles N. Tenney to Adelaide E. Case, <date value="1861-12-11"
                        >December 11, 1861</date></head>
                <pb n="1" entity="DSSR_000000766_0413"/>


                <opener>
                    <dateline><name type="place">Parkersburg <abbr expan="Virginia">Va</abbr></name><lb/>
                        <date value="1862-12-11">Dec 11<hi rend="super">th</hi> 1861</date>. </dateline>
                    <lb/>

                    <salute>My dear Addie:</salute>
                </opener>


                <p>Here we are, right<lb/> in sight of loyal<name type="place">Ohio</name> but<lb/>
                        refus<del hand="h1">ing</del><add place="inline" hand="h1">ed</add> the
                        privil<del hand="h1">i</del><add place="inline" hand="h1">e</add>ge of
                    entering<lb/> within its borders, the authorities<lb/> preferring that we should
                    remain<lb/> on the &ldquo;sacred soil of <name type="place"
                    >Virginia</name>.&rdquo;<lb/> But we are not long to have<lb/> the privilege
                    even of looking at<lb/> the <name type="place">Ohio</name> Shore, for at four
                    P.M.<lb/> we take the R. R. for <name type="place">Grafton</name>.<lb/> From
                    thence I suppose we go to<lb/> the end of the world,&mdash; <name
                        type="place">Romney</name>.<lb/> Well, as I am denied the happine&longs;s<lb/>
                    <pb n="2" entity="DSSR_000000766_0414"/> of seeing my <name type="person"
                    >Addie</name>. I will resort<lb/> to the only feasible expedient, that of<lb/>
                    conversation on paper.</p>

                <p> My health is good, how is yours<lb/>
                     <name type="person">Addie</name>, dear? How glad I am that<lb/> writing was
                    invented long ago, and<lb/> that I have a good memory, for<lb/> I seem to
                        see <orig reg="you,">you.</orig> sitting by your<lb/> sweet toned
                        melodeon<ref target="n1" n="1">1</ref>, your soul<lb/> giving utterance to
                    its goodne&longs;s<lb/> in happy song, the music of which<lb/> seems to
                    reach me, and enliven<lb/> my inmost spirit. How glad am<lb/> I, <del hand="h1"
                        rend="slash-through">that</del> to know and feel that you<lb/> are at this
                    moment holding me in<lb/> kind remembrance. Happine&longs;s, is a<lb/> boon
                    many strive to reach, but few,<lb/> comparatively, attain, but if
                    happine&longs;s<lb/> exists among soldiers, it is him, who<lb/> knows that
                    there is a heart which<lb/> beats in unison with his own, and<lb/> feels that <hi
                        rend="underline">her</hi> spirit is watching over<lb/> him, that is the
                    fortunate possessor.<lb/>
                    <pb n="3" entity="DSSR_000000766_0415"/> Am I mistaken in believing that<lb/>
                    there is one who thus remembers<lb/> me, and that one, <name type="person"
                    >Addie</name>? Forgive<lb/> me <orig reg="if I do">if do</orig> wrong in thus
                        plainly <orig reg="expressing">expre&longs;s-<lb/> ing</orig> myself, for
                    it is the promptings of my<lb/> heart, and my conscience reproves me often<lb/>
                    for not doing as I ought. I speak thus<lb/> to hush its reproving voice. But,
                    although<lb/> our acquaintance has been short, has it<lb/> been productive of
                    ill? has your heart not<lb/> been moved in unison with mine? but I'll<lb/> bide
                    my time, perhaps I may meet<lb/> you again. Forgive me if I have done wrong. </p>

                <p>In a few short hours, we leave<lb/> the pleasant view of <name type="place"
                    >Ohio</name>, and retreat<lb/> to the wilds of <name type="place"
                    >Virginia</name>, perhaps never<lb/> to return, for I learn by the way that<lb/>
                    we are to enter the field again. If I fall<lb/> I fall in the defense of my once
                    happy<lb/> country. I shall die, "unwept, unhonored,<lb/> and unknown;" but of
                    this, in the main,<lb/> I care not, all I wish to know is<lb/> that if I fall I
                    shall be regretted by <hi rend="underline">one</hi>.<lb/>
                    <pb n="4" entity="DSSR_000000766_0416"/> Assured that such is the <orig
                        reg="case, I">case. I</orig> die <orig reg="happy.">happy</orig><lb/> But <del
                        hand="h1" rend="line-through">le&longs;s</del> lest I weary you I will
                    change<lb/> the subject. We left <name type="place">Charleston</name>
                    yesterday<lb/> at 2 P.M. on the steamer &ldquo; <name type="ship"
                    >Decatur</name>&rdquo;<lb/> and arrived at <name type="place">Pt.
                    Pleasant</name> at 7.40<lb/> we rode all night, most of the time<lb/> racing
                    with the <name type="ship"> <orig reg="Fort">Fort.</orig> Wayne</name> on<lb/>
                    which was part of the <abbr expan="regiment">Regt</abbr>. At<lb/> about 11.30
                    A.M. to day we arrived<lb/> here. I suppose as the <name type="regiment"
                    >Seventh</name> is<lb/> accredited as a good <abbr expan="regiment">Regt.</abbr>
                    we must<lb/> keep our name by <hi rend="underline">deserving</hi> <orig reg="it."
                        >it</orig></p>

                <closer>
                    <salute> But I must close. Forgive all<lb/> errors and <orig reg="mistakes, as"
                            >mistakes. as</orig> I am writing<lb/> in the cabin of the <name
                            type="ship">Decatur</name>, and all<lb/> is <orig reg="confusion, and"
                            >confusion. and</orig> write soon to Your true</salute>
                    <signed>
                         <name type="person">Charlie</name>
                    </signed>,<lb/> I will send you our addre&longs;s as soon<lb/> as I learn
                    where it is. <name type="person">Hal</name> urges your and <orig reg="Laurie's"
                        >Lauries</orig> going<lb/> to <name type="place">Oberlin</name>, and sends a
                        note. <orig reg="My">my</orig> respects<lb/> to all and love to <name
                        type="person">Addie</name>. </closer>


            </div1>
        </body>


        <back id="d6">

